properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Significant snowfall and strong winds are expected. Freezing precipitation is also possible over some areas. Locations: Churchill Falls and Churchill Valley. Total snowfall: 20 cm or more. Maximum wind gusts: northwesterly 80 km/h or higher Sunday night into Monday. Time span: tonight until Monday morning. Remarks: Snow will begin this evening and may become heavy at times Sunday morning. The snow is likely to change to ice pellets or freezing rain on Sunday but will transition back to snow Sunday night. A brief period of rain is possible Sunday evening before changing back to snow. Strong northwesterly winds are also expected to develop Sunday night, resulting in poor visibility in blowing snow. Anyone planning weather sensitive activities is advised to plan ahead. Travel is expected to become difficult as a result of these conditions. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NLstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NLwx.

properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A winter storm with mixed precipitation on the way for this weekend. Locations: Upper Lake Melville, Eagle River, and along the coast from Postville - Makkovik to Lodge Bay. Total snowfall: 5 to 10 cm, higher amounts possible in Postville - Makkovik. Total rainfall: 10 to 20 mm south of Groswater Bay. Lesser amounts elsewhere. Maximum wind gusts: easterly 80 km/h. Time span: tonight into Sunday night. Remarks: Snow will develop this evening over southeastern Labrador and spread to central and the remainder of coast through the night. The snow will change through ice pellets and freezing rain to rain on Sunday. Central and inland areas of coastal Labrador could see several hours of freezing rain during the changeover. The rainfall, combined with temperatures above zero late in the day on Sunday could result in significant snowmelt in some areas, especially coastal areas south of Groswater Bay. Anyone planning weather sensitive activities is advised to plan ahead. Travel is expected to become difficult as a result of these conditions. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NLstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NLwx.

properties.Title: Special Air Quality Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: The Ministry of Environment and Climate Change Strategy in collaboration with Northern Health has issued an Air Quality Advisory for Houston because of high concentrations of fine particulate matter. This advisory is in effect until further notice. Persons with chronic underlying medical conditions should postpone strenuous exercise until the advisory is lifted. Staying indoors and in air conditioned spaces helps to reduce fine particulate exposure. Exposure is particularly a concern for pregnant women, infants, the elderly and those who have diabetes, and lung or heart disease. For the duration of this advisory the use of woodstoves is prohibited within the Districtof Houston, unless the woodstove is the only source of heat in a dwelling. Real-time air quality observations and information regarding the health effects of air pollution can be found at https://www2.gov.bc.ca/gov/content/environment/air-land-water/air ### For more information on current air quality, visit www2.gov.bc.ca/gov/content/environment/air-land-water/air. Visit www.airhealth.ca for information on how to reduce your health risk and your personal contribution to pollution levels, as well as for current and forecast AQHI values. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada.
